<section>
    <h4>Current Features and Development Stage</h4>
    <p>As of August 20, 2022, Wafis supports several core features. These include the use of TSX components, building TypeScript components, custom tag rendering, and limited AssemblyScript functionality within the build project command. Despite its nascent stage, the framework shows promise with these operational features. However, developers should note that it is still in the early stages of development, and they may encounter incomplete features and areas under construction.</p>
    <h4>Planned Enhancements and Future Capabilities</h4>
    <p>Looking forward, the development roadmap for Wafis includes significant expansions. Future updates aim to incorporate C++ with Emscripten, a dependency package system based on Napa, and Rust integration using webpack for Rust WASM modules. Additional planned features include API services, enhanced CLI options (e.g., more sophisticated component creation commands), CSS encapsulation for individual components, a main configuration file for various project settings, and advanced testing capabilities with Cypress. The framework also aims to support data attributes, class extensions to custom tags, SCSS integration, and Angular-like directives.</p>
</section>
